d expanded through two centuries of struggle and that Americans are now institutionalizing as a "new normal" the abuse of rights in the name of national security. He expands this hypothesis to the global level through what he calls "the international state of emergency."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aPolitics and war. 0aVietnam War, 1961-1975xPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aWar on Terrorism, 2001-2009xPolitical aspectszUnited States. 4aMilitary History. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aU.S. History.  aPolitical discontent, social movements, disruption of the status quo, war & society, globalization, conflict between states, national security.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080145624440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801456244423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801456244/original  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles